title: Fans Say Domino‚Äôs New Menu Item Is Oven-Baked Perfection
text:
By Yasmine Coleman ,
2 hours ago
Domino's is continuing its foray into offering foods other than pizza, and its new menu item already has fans drooling.
On Wednesday, Sept. 18, food blogger Markie Devo took to Instagram to share news of the chain's latest addition: Mac & Cheese.
There are said to be two different flavors of the creamy dish, which the foodie described in the post's caption. "5-Cheese Mac & Cheese features penne pasta combined with a blend of cheddar, American, Parmesan-Asiago, mozzarella blend, and Alfredo sauce ‚Äì all oven-baked to creamy, bubbly perfection," he explained, while "Spicy Buffalo 5-Cheese Mac & Cheese adds a flavorful twist to the classic dish, as it is drizzled with hot buffalo sauce."
The big move makes sense for the brand, given that the eatery already offers a variety of oven-baked pastas prepared using the same type of noodles, including Chicken Alfredo, Italian Sausage Marinara, Chicken Carbonara, Pasta Primavera, as well as a Build Your Own option.
The foodie insider further shared that curious tastebuds eager to try out the new menu items can do so once they are made available at Domino‚Äôs locations nationwide starting on Sept. 23, 2024.
In the comment section of the upload, fans expressed excitement for Domino's twist on the cult classic meal.
"Definitely YAYYY. I just had a pasta bowl from them earlier üòÇ," one expressed, while another simply said "They sound good."
"If only these had chicken in them ü§§ü§§," a third wished, as another follower recalled, "they used to have mac n cheese like 10 years ago! it was really good."
Meanwhile, someone else suggested a minor tweak when ordering: "I know certain locations still do it on request but this in a bread bowl would hit so differently ü§§."

author: JEFF AMY
title: Georgia bill aims to protect religious liberty. Opponents say it's a license to discriminate - The San Diego Union-Tribune
text: Georgia bill aims to protect religious liberty. Opponents say it‚Äôs a license to discriminate Georgia lawmakers are revisiting a nearly decade-old fight over whether the state needs to protect religious rights from being trampled by state and local governments in a measure opponents say would provide a legal shield for people and groups to discriminate against LGBTQ+ people in the name of religion. That religious protection bill resurfaced Thursday eight years after lawmakers passed a different version of the measure. Then-Gov. Nathan Deal, a Republican, vetoed it in 2016 under pressure from Georgia‚Äôs business community, who said they feared it would hurt their ability to attract employees and tourists. Also Thursday, a House subcommittee advanced a measure that would ban transgender students in public schools from using the bathroom that meets their current gender identity. Supporters say the measure is needed to protect students who aren‚Äôt transgender, while opponents in sometimes tearful testimony told lawmakers the measure would stigmatize and endanger transgender students who are already subject to bullying. Both measures are being pushed in an election year when all of Georgia‚Äôs lawmakers are up for reelection and Republican leaders have become more conservative. The Senate Judiciary Committee voted 6-3 to pass Senate Bill 180, sending it on to the full Senat for more debate. It mirrors a 1993 federal law, the Religious Freedom Restoration Act. The bill‚Äôs sponsor, Republican Sen. Ed Setzler of Acworth, has pushed for the measure for years, because the federal law doesn‚Äôt apply to state and local governments, which might deny things like permission to distribute religious literature or a zoning permit for a church without giving enough deference to religious freedom. ‚ÄúEvery Georgian should be free to worship and exercise their faith without unfair federal, state or local government intrusion,‚Äù Setzler said. But opponents warn that private businesses will use the law to do things like deny birth control coverage to their employees, and the legislation could blow holes in local laws that ban discrimination. Georgia has no statewide law banning discrimination. ‚ÄúIt seems like some people have a hate agenda in their religious practices, to deny jobs, housing and dignity to gays and lesbians,‚Äù said Michael Rohtbaum, senior rabbi at Congregation Bet Haverim, an Atlanta synagogue. Setzler, though says claims that the bill would enable discrimination are spurious. ‚ÄúWhat they‚Äôre saying is just simply not so,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúThe parade of horribles you heard is just simply not so when you look at the states that this applies to.‚Äù The current bill has 23 other Republican senators as cosigners, but the issue has languished, seen as politically radioactive after Deal‚Äôs veto. The debate over the bill to regulate student bathroom use has the same outlines, with Republicans saying Georgians need protection and opponents saying the law will be weaponized against transgender students. ‚ÄúThe issue is making sure biological males use the male facilities and biological females use the female facilities,‚Äù said Rep. Josh Bonner, a Fayetteville Republican who is sponsoring House Bill 936. Elizabeth Wagner of suburban Berkeley Lake told committee members she‚Äôs the mother of a transgender boy. She warned the bill would only amp up bullying by forcing him to use the girls‚Äô bathroom. ‚ÄúAnyone with a heart and a handful of brain cells can see this bill for what it is,‚Äù Wagner said. ‚ÄúIt is open hunting season on trans youth in Georgia.‚Äù The measure also covers locker rooms and overnight school trips. It requires that schools find some other bathroom for transgender or other students uncomfortable using the bathroom that matches their birth sex. It was unclear from committee debate whether any Georgia school district has a policy that allows transgender students to use bathrooms corresponding with their current gender identity. But opponents said that alternate restrooms can often involve a trek across a large high school campus, making it hard for students to access during the school day. Ben Ackerley, who helps lead the Georgia chapter of TransParent, a group for parents of transgender youth, said it also adds to students‚Äô isolation. ‚ÄúThat accommodation keeps them separate from their peers, and all they want to do is be included,‚Äù Ackerley said. The Movement Advancement Project, a group that advocates for LGBTQ+ rights, says 11 states have passed bills regulating bathroom usage since 2021, including neighboring Tennessee, Alabama and Florida. North Carolina passed in 2016 and repealed in 2017 amid the same kind of controversy that led Deal to veto Georgia‚Äôs religious liberty bill in 2016. Georgia‚Äôs measure would let parents sue school districts if school officials let students use a bathroom that doesn‚Äôt match their birth sex, and it would let the Professional Standards Commission, which licenses teachers and administrators, to investigate noncompliance. text:
'Enverdecimiento' r√©cord: la superficie vegetal de Groenlandia se duplic√≥ en 30 a√±os 06:43 GMT Uno de los peligros que lleva aparejado este fen√≥meno es el aumento de la superficie de los humedales, que son una fuente de emisi√≥n de metano, un gas de efecto invernadero.
Icebergs flotando frente al pueblo de Ilulissat, Groenlandia. Eloi_Omella / Gettyimages.ru Contrariamente a lo que sugiere su nombre hist√≥rico, la isla de Groenlandia no es nada verde: cuatro quintas partes de su territorio est√°n cubiertas por glaciares milenarios.
Sin embargo, un an√°lisis de im√°genes de sat√©lite de 1980 a 2010 revel√≥ que el calentamiento global est√° cambiando este panorama muy r√°pidamente, seg√∫n un estudio liderado por la Universidad de Leeds, Reino Unido.
El an√°lisis de registros satelitales hist√≥ricos de esas tres d√©cadas, publicado en la revista Scientific Reports , mostr√≥ que en ese tiempo se derritieron 28.707 kil√≥metros cuadrados de la capa de hielo y glaciares de Groenlandia, lo que equivale al tama√±o de Albania y ronda un 1,6 % del manto helado de la isla, la m√°s grande del mundo.
La humanidad podr√≠a subestimar la magnitud de la futura subida del nivel del mar, alerta un estudio Adem√°s, durante las tres d√©cadas estudiadas, la cantidad de tierra cubierta con vegetaci√≥n aument√≥ m√°s del doble (111 %), a√±adiendo unos 87.475 kil√≥metros cuadrados de tundra, matorrales, pantanos y pastizales.
Sorprendentemente, el √°rea de masas de agua dulce ha disminuido en un 10 %, aunque el margen de error en los datos es grande y a√∫n no es posible verificar de manera confiable este par√°metro.
La superficie de humedales es la que m√°s ha aumentado, casi cuadruplic√°ndose, y ahora ocupa 30.300 kil√≥metros cuadrados. Los humedales son una fuente de emisiones de metano.
"La expansi√≥n de la vegetaci√≥n, especialmente en las zonas de humedales, indica, pero tambi√©n exacerba, el deshielo del permafrost, el engrosamiento de la capa activa y, por tanto, las emisiones de gases de efecto invernadero previamente almacenados en estos suelos √°rticos", se√±ala el art√≠culo.
El equipo investigador sugiere que el retroceso del hielo a su vez est√° teniendo un impacto en la temperatura de la superficie terrestre, las emisiones de gases de efecto invernadero y la estabilidad del paisaje.
"La p√©rdida de masa de hielo en Groenlandia contribuye sustancialmente al aumento global del nivel del mar, una tendencia que plantea importantes desaf√≠os tanto ahora como en el futuro", se√±al√≥ el ge√≥grafo Michael Grimes, uno de los autores del estudio.
